post_text:
Below is information that was emailed to all parents today. Additional information will be shared as soon as it is available. Please do not hesitate calling the district office with questions or concerns.

ENROLLMENT: If you have not completed the on-line portion of enrollment for your students, please do so before coming to complete the in-person portion of enrollment next Monday or Tuesday, August 3 or 4, @ KJSH lunchroom. This will help the process to run more smoothly.

REMINDER: Students entering Pre-school and Kindergarten need a physical and immunizations must be up to date prior to school starting. If these things have been taken care of, please bring the information to enrollment so that copies can be made and filed. Students entering 7th grade will need a Tdap and Meningococcal immunizations. 11th graders need to have Meningococcal immunizations updated.

post_text:
Today, in a 5-5 vote, the KS State Board of Education rejected Gov. Laura Kelly's order requiring K-12 schools to start after Labor Day. This now gives local school boards the authority to continue to decide when classes will begin for their district.

Our Administration, Board of Education and Teachers will be discussing a suitable start date for the Coyotes. They also continue to work on a plan that will accommodate the educational needs of ALL kids.

Any Kinsley people that want to help me get this started please share and get the word around!

Friday night at 8pm we are going back to high school days and cruising Kinsley!! Hope to see you there!

Under the advisement of The Kansas State Board of Education, Kansas Commissioner of Education, and the Governor of Kansas, Kinsley-Offerle schools will be closed the entire week from March 16-20, 2020. Obviously, we are on Spring Break, so this means all practices are cancelled and no access will be granted to the school gyms.

The district office and 12 month staff will report to work.

Information will be shared as it becomes available.

“In the end, it will be impossible to know if we over reacted or did too much, but it will be QUITE apparent if we under reacted or did too little” - Dr. Daniel Hile, Supt Smith-Green Community Schools

post_text:
SPRING BREAK has officially started! We hope our staff and students get some much needed REST and RELAXATION and can return March 23 ready to finish the year out STRONG! And HEALTHY!

However....with the COVID-19 scare, we will keep parents, staff and the community informed of information as it becomes available.

School administration has been in contact with the County Health Department, Edwards County Medical Center, KDHE (KS Dept of Health & Environment), KSDE (KS Dept of Education) and KASB (KS Association of School Boards) regarding guidelines and recommendations on how to plan for a possible pandemic. The recurring message from all of these agencies is to practice good hand washing, cover your cough and to stay home if you are sick.

Thank you to Mrs. Burkhart for sharing some ways to help with anxiety concerning Coronavirus.
